'''5 Kanal''' ({{lang-uk|5 канал}}; {{lang-en|Channel 5}}) is a television station in [[Ukraine]] controlled by businessman and [[President of Ukraine]] [[Petro Poroshenko]].<ref name=poro5>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/67473/ Poroshenko is not going to sell Channel 5 TV], [[Kyiv Post]] (May 23, 2010)</ref>
The channel became well known as the first major broadcaster during the [[Ukrainian presidential election, 2004|2004 presidential election]] offering critical broadcasting on candidate [[Viktor Yanukovych]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3747594.stm |title=Ukraine TV stokes election battle. |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=2004-10-20}}</ref> The whole staff of the channel went on [[hunger strike]] when (at the time, late 2004) the government threatened to close it.<ref name=APOR291011>[https://www.academia.edu/1068864/Russia_the_US_the_Others_and_the_101_Things_to_Do_to_Win_a_Colour_Revolution_Reflections_on_Georgia_and_Ukraine Russia, the US, “the Others” and the “101 Things to Do to Win a (Colour)Revolution”: Reflections on Georgia and Ukraine] by [[Abel Polese]], [[Routledge]] (26 October 2011)</ref>
According to the Ukrainian [[media watchdog]] ''[[Telekrytyka]]'' Kanal 5 and [[TVi (channel)|TVi]] were the only remaining TV channels mid-May 2010 with independent and fair TV news coverage.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/66674/ Media expert: Only two TV stations still give viewers fair news coverage], [[Kyiv Post]] (May 13, 2010)</ref>
==Anchors & Correspondents== * [[Andriy Shevchenko (politician)|Andriy Shevchenko]] (2003–05), * [[Roman Skrypin]] (2003–06), * [[Hanna Homonai]] (2004), * Yevhen Hlibovytsky (2005–06), * Svyatoslav Tseholko (2004-2014), * Lidiya Taran (2006–09)
