{{unreferenced|date=April 2018}}
'''Banū al-Akhdari''' (in [[Arabic]] : بنو الأخضري / banū al-Akẖḍarī, "the Lakhdari Clan") are a [[Sharif|Shereefian]] [[Arab]] [[tribe]] from [[Hejaz|Western Arabia]]. They immigrated during the advent of Islam to [[Yemen]] and the region of [[Rub' al Khali]] and [[Hadhramaut]] and then to the [[Maghreb]] more precisely in [[Algeria]] with the [[Maqil|Banu Maqil]] tribe from the 7th century. Their descendants bear the surnames "Lakhdari, al-Akhdari and el-Akhdari", they are cousins with the [[Banu Hashim]] tribe, [[Banu Kinanah]] tribe and the [[Senussi|Banu al-Senussi]] [[tribe]] and members of the [[Quraysh]] branch.

They are the direct descendants of their common ancestors [[Hashim ibn Abd Manaf|'Amr Hashim Ibn' Abd Manaf]] (in [[Arabic]] : عامر هاشم بن عبد مناف) who was the great-grandfather of the [[Prophet]] of Islam [[Muhammad]].

