The '''cinema of Namibia''' refers to cinema in the country of [[Namibia]], which claimed independence from [[South Africa]] in 1990.

Before independence, American anthropologist [[John Marshall (filmmaker)|John Marshall]] made ethnographic films of the [[Ju/'hoansi]] for over four decades from 1950 onwards, resulting in documentary films such as ''[[The Hunters (1957 film)|The Hunters]]'' (1957) and ''[[Nǃai, the Story of a ǃKung Woman]]'' (1980).<ref name=remembering>Apley, Alice and David Tamés. (June 2005) [http://newenglandfilm.com/magazine/2005/07/remembering-john-marshall-1932-2005 Remembering John Marshall (1932–2005)] newenglandfilm.com Retrieved 1 Aug 2008.</ref>

After independence, Namibian filmmakers have started to assert their own identity. Pioneers included [[Bridget Pickering]], [[Richard Pakleppa]] and [[Cecil Moller]]. They have been joined by a younger generation including [[Joel Haikali]], [[Oshosheni Hiveluah]], [[Perivi Katjavivi]], [[Tim Huebschle]],<ref name="SaralaHelen2018">{{cite book|last=Mahnke|first=Hans-Christian|editor=Krishnamurthy, Sarala; Vale, Helen|title=Writing Namibia: Literature in Transition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=okZbDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA211|year=2018|publisher=University of Namibia Press|isbn=978-99916-42-33-8|page=211|chapter=Reading Namibian film}}</ref> and [[Krischka Stoffels]].<ref name="NelmesSelbo2015">{{cite book|author=Jule Selbo|editor=Jill Nelmes; Jule Selbo|title=Women Screenwriters: An International Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGikCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29|year=2015|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-31237-2|page=29}}</ref>

In 2000, the Namibian government passed the [[Namibian Film Commission Act]] to promote filmmaking in the country.<ref name="NelmesSelbo2015"/>

